  "signature": "ed25519:b1c2d3e4f5a6b7c8d9e0f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1e2f3a4b5c6d7e8f9a0b1c2d3e4f5a6b7c8d9e0f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1e2f3a4b5c6d7e8f9a0b1c2",
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-accepted-20260419",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/actor/dr-a-morrison",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team lead",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The Morrison COU1 credibility assessment is accepted based on the following structured evidence synthesis. All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed and all achieve levels meeting or exceeding their required levels for Model Risk Level 2. Key findings: (1) Software quality assurance — commercial solver with ISO 9001 certification and independently verified UDF (SQA Gradation 2 achieved). (2) Numerical code verification — MMS-confirmed second-order accuracy; scalar transport error 0.29% (NCV Gradation 2). (3) Discretisation error — GCI_fine 1.8% on NIH, exceeding MRL 2 requirement (Gradation 3 achieved). (4) Test conditions — boundary conditions within 1.5% of experimental targets. (5) Output comparison — NIH MAPE 11.4% overall, 7.3% at worst-case point; pressure head MAPE 3.2%; both within acceptance criteria. (6) QoI relevance — NIH and RH directly traceable to ASTM F1841 regulatory criterion. (7) Validation relevance — all five COU operating points directly validated against identical-geometry FDA experimental data. (8) Numerical solver error — iterative residuals and QoI convergence within acceptance thresholds. (9) Use error — independent peer review and post-processing reproducibility confirmed. (10) Model form — RANS-SST k-ω and Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law justified by ≥2 peer-reviewed publications. (11) Model inputs — input traceability matrix complete; uncertainty ranges assigned; dominant input identified. (12) Test samples — dimensional inspection confirms geometry equivalence within 0.5%. (13) Equivalency of input parameters — all deviations < 2% against acceptance threshold of 5%. Sensitivity analysis confirms model conclusions are robust to haemolysis coefficient uncertainty (rank ordering preserved in 97% of LHS realisations). The model correctly identifies the worst-case hemolysis operating condition (6 L/min / 3500 RPM) with RH < 1 relative to the predicate device. The credibility evidence is sufficient to support the regulatory submission decision for this Class II CPB device at MRL 2.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
